You can still see it in your mind's eye, clear as crystal.  Old man Simmons taking that ten-cent stinker of a cigar out of his mouth long enough to announce that you've been chosen for special assignment as a foreign correspondent.  Vince, the sportswriter, clapping you on the back and shaking your hand.   Maybelle slipping that little flask of bootleg hooch she always carries out of her purse and offering you a celebratory swig.  Reggie flashing your one of those dreamy smiles that would have had you walking on air even if you hadn't just gotten the promotion of your life.

Just think of it!  You, Jacqueline McBean, a foreign correspondent at the tender age of twenty--and you didn't get it by batting your baby blues around the office or anything like that, but by good, solid journalism.  You brought in the scoops nobody else could get, and gee whiz, did it ever pay off in spades!  You didn't even know the Fresno Bee HAD a foreign correspondent, and now you're her!

As you boarded the rickety two-seater plane destined for Golanaland's glittering capitol city, you probably could have flapped your arms and taken off yourself, you were so thrilled.

You wonder what  happened to that optimism as the plane corkscrews towards the dark heart of the unexplored Golanalese jungle.  Oh, that's right!  It bailed out around fifteen miles back, along with the pilot and the only parachute.   He didn't want to abandon you but, honestly, after both engines burst into flames and the roof peeled away like a metal banana peel, you can't blame him for getting a few ants in his pants.

Such a short life, and so many regrets!  You'll never win a Pulitzer.  You'll never bring down a corrupt presidency.  You'll never get to eat another one of your mother's famous six-meat meatballs.

But at least you got to travel.

You don't remember much about the actual crash, just smears of green and blue as the world whipped about you, followed by nothingness.  All you remember is waking up here, on the floor of the plane, your body bruised and battered and your head throbbing.   You put a hand to your temples and feel blood.  Well, if that isn't just the cat's pajamas -- but at least you're alive.

You struggle to your feet, feeling the floor shift unsteadily under your weight, and look around.

The Spirit of Fresno
You're in the cabin of The Spirit of Fresno, the plucky little plane that couldn't.    It's missing its roof, both wings, and the exit door, and leaves are drifting down from the damaged canopy above.   A thick branch has torn through the floor, revealing a dizzying drop to the underbrush far below.

There's a sound above you like crickets chirping, or maybe it's like frogs croaking, or birdsong, or maybe it's like all of them at once--and the funny thing is, you could swear it's calling your name.   There's enough of the metal frame remaining that you could probably haul yourself up on the roof of the plane, and you feel a strange compulsion to do just that.

You can see a Guidebook to Golanaland and a radio.
> x me

> x me
You're wearing a short-sleeved shirt, khaki shorts, and your trusty vest with thirty-eight pockets.  Your red hair is tied back in a loose ponytail.
> x guidebook

> x guidebook
A thick guide containing all the information you need to survive your Golanaland experience.
> read it

> read it
"Welcome to paradise!   In the following seven hundred and fifty pages, we'll tell you everything you need to know about the prosperous utopia of Golanaland, from how to tip properly while staying in Gola City's many luxurious hotels to which restaurants are utterly sublime and which are merely excellent.   Lost?  No problem!  See the full fold out map of the ultramodern Golarail Transport System, which can whisk you anywhere in the country in mere minutes!   From the shopaholic to the gambler to the history buff, there's something for everyone in this glittering emerald country of lush parkland and shining skyscrapers.

While the Golanese are a progressive, cosmopolitan people with a strong tradition of hospitality and the highest level of education in the world, they maintain a strong connection to their heritage, including beliefs that seem quirky to outsiders.  For instance, the old Golanese belief in 'word wizards' means that writers, speechmakers, and journalists are especially revered, feted at every opportunity and showered with gifts.  And did you know that the Golanese traditionally believe that red hair is a sign of divine blood?    It's true!  Many a redheaded visitor has been bemused to find themselves the center of attention, with the most attractive men and women in the country competing for their favor.

Before we begin our journey, one note of caution: occasionally, visitors with an interest in wildlife will be lured into taking shady 'tours' into Darkest Golanaland, the wild heart of the country.  Don't be a fool!  Central Golanaland is an incredibly harsh and dangerous land crawling with some of the most deadly wildlife on Earth.    It's so inhospitable that to provide any details on how to survive there or specific warnings about its dangers would only encourage people to risk their lives foolishly.   Stick with Gola City's many natural history museums, and leave the jungle alone!"
> x radio

> x radio
A dashboard-mounted radio set with attractive wood paneling.
> turn on radio

> turn on radio
The cabin is filled with the jaunty sounds of Bix Bigby and his Big Boy Band.
> turn off radio

> turn off radio
Bix Bigby flies the coop.
> u

> u
Standing on the back of the pilot's chair, you haul yourself up to balance on the remains of the metal frame.

The Green Shrine
You're standing on top of the plane, high up in the canopy, a castaway in an ocean of green.   A strange idol, about the size of your head, is embedded in the trunk of the enormous tree--you could walk right up to it if you balance on the left wing of the plane.    All of the trees surrounding you are overgrown, but the one you're stuck  in seems particularly saturated with life, dripping with vines and bromeliads, the bark almost taut over the burgeoning wood.   The branches are heavy with golanuts and thousands of flying squirrels. Most of them are out of reach, but one golanut is hanging low enough that you might just be able to take it if you stand on your toes.
You can see a mossy idol.
> x idol

> x idol
This roughly carved face is frozen in an animal snarl.  The idol appears to have been carved from moist limestone, though it's difficult to tell because it's so overgrown with moss and fungus, which covers not just the idol but the trunk around it.  Despite the cruel expression, it seems somehow to beckon you.  You feel an overwhelming desire to TOUCH it.
> touch it

> touch it
As your fingers brush against the idol, energy pours out of it in a torrent, as if you've just thrust your fist into an electrical transformer.   You're frozen in place, your mind flooded with images.    You see yourself as strong as a gorilla, as stealthy as a panther, as flexible as a snake, and even soaring through the sky like a bird.   Somehow, you know that all these things are possible now, if you could only find the right animals and learn their secrets.

You now have the ability to learn special powers from animals!  You can MIMIC any animal you encounter in order to learn their abilities.
> x squirrels

> x squirrels
They're gliding around in the upper branches, licking at the golanuts as if they're trying to get at the meat within.
> x golanut

> x golanut
A large green nut about the size and shape of a bowling ball.   It's so ripe it looks ready to burst.
> take it

> take it
You scrabble at the golanut with your fingertips.  It's just barely out of reach.   If only you could jump--but your footing is so precarious, you don't dare.   Finally, stretching as far as you can, you manage to get a firm grip and pull the nut free.   You try to catch it, but fumble, and the nut tumbles through the metal frame to burst in a ripe explosion on the cabin floor.

You smell the fruity fumes rising from the cabin almost at once.  It looks like the flying squirrels smell the same--hundreds of them plunge hungrily past you, swarming into the plane to feast.
> d

> d
You drop carelessly back into the cabin, wincing as the plane shifts beneath your weight.

The Spirit of Fresno
You're in the cabin of The Spirit of Fresno, the plucky little plane that couldn't.    It's missing its roof, both wings, and the exit door, and leaves are drifting down from the damaged canopy above.   A thick branch has torn through the floor, revealing a dizzying drop to the underbrush far below.

Golden light filters through the metal frame, making a lattice of shadows on the floor.

You can see a Guidebook to Golanaland, a burst golanut, flying squirrels and a radio.
> x squirrels

> x squirrels
They're cute, fuzzy things, small enough to hold in your hand, although when there are hundreds of them squirming all over each other the impression is a little less adorable.   Most of them are slurping at the fruit like pigs at a trough, but there are plenty of them in the air, too, gliding freely around the cabin.  It looks like the Spirit of Fresno will spend its retirement as a squirrel nesting ground.
> x golanut

> x golanut
It was so ripe that it burst on impact, splattering juicy meat all over the cabin.
> mimic squirrels

> mimic squirrels
As you focus on the squirrels, you feel a deep understanding awakening in you.  You know what it's like to soar on currents of air, to feel the wind in your outstretched skin membranes, to taste the sweet taste of semi-spoiled golanut.   You feel confident that now, with a fundamental knowledge of the nature of the flying squirrel, you can glide down from any height safely.
> d

> d
You spread your arms wide and topple out of the open door, half expecting to become a flap-Jacq.  But the air buoys you, slowing your fall, and you glide spread-eagled to the forest floor.

A Tangle of Roots
You are in a gnarled tangle of enormous roots at the foot of the tree.    A broad, worn path travels past you in a north-south direction, and the heaps of crumbling stonework visible through the roots seems to indicate that there was once some sort of a building where the tree now grows.   High above you, you can just make out the plane tangled in the branches.

You can see a vital component.
> x component

> x component
It's a Electro-2000 Modular Static Aeroplane Radio Interociter, used for making outgoing transmissions.    A notice on the side brags that the Electro-2000 detaches and falls out of the bottom of the plane at the slightest jostle, for easier cleaning, and proceeds to give easy-to-follow instructions for reinstalling the unit.  All you need is the component and the radio together and you'll be communicating like a champ!
