Fancy Quarters
These quarters may have been opulent before the roof collapsed, but two hundred years of exposure to the elements haven't done them any favors.  A faded four-poster bed squats in the middle of the room.  Against one wall, an aquarium sits on top of a solid oak chest of drawers.    The door to the tavern is to the east.   A large portrait of a pirate hangs on the opposite wall.
You can see an aquarium.
> x bed

> x bed
It looks like a squashed sandwich somebody put in their pocket, forgot about, and sat on.   You've made do with the old pastrami-and-keester a few times yourself, but you doubt you could bring yourself to sleep in this bed.
> x aquarium

> x aquarium
This fifty-gallon cut crystal aquarium may have been part of the captain's treasure, but he obviously had a practical use for it as well, because it contains a single well-fed guard piranha.   The aquarium is brimming with clean-looking water thanks to the last rain, which must be how the fish stays topped up.

In the center of the aquarium, you spot a tantalizing gold key resting on a decorative pillar.
> x piranha

> x piranha
A proud warrior, the descendent of the original river piranhas the pirate captain must have been keeping as pets.  A layer of bird bones on the bottom of the tank clue you in on how he's managed to survive in there so long.   He's swimming around the stone pillar in the middle of the tank, obviously hoping you'll be birdbrained enough to reach in.
> x key

> x key
A delicately carved gold key, the head of which is shaped like a treble clef.   It gives you flashbacks to long and boring hours doing scales on the piano.
> x pillar

> x pillar
This squat stone pillar is raised to about the middle of the aquarium.  A shiny gold key lies temptingly on the flat top of the column.
> x drawers

> x drawers
A heavy oak chest of drawers.  It's solid and weatherworn, but it should still be possible to open and close it.
> open drawers

> open drawers
You open it.
It contains a neat page, a torn page, a crumpled page, a yellowed page and a tin of Guff.
> read neat page

> read neat page
"July 26th, 1710.

No luck again hunting but the Captain has discovered a most curious Statue the effects of which upon him are scarce to be believed; however if must be said the chief Effect so far as we are concerned is that the Small Beer which was supposed to last us through the Year is now gone in scarce a Week and still no Meat to be had.  Skinny John has said we ought to eat Rosie but the Captain would have none of it as she is akin to his Flesh and Blood and he set John to swabbing the Decks.   Anyway I am glad as I would not like to eat Rosie for she is a part of the Crew & would surely have not much meat anyway & also we have fruit."
> read torn page

> read torn page
"August 13, 1710

Whatever cruel force now animates Skinny John it is not the same one found in the Captain for his thirst is insatiable & his desperation fearsome.   Mad Old Jane said that this was his punishment for Treachery and Thieving from our own & the bastard killed her on the spot & drained her like a man drinking from a Wineskin.   Rosie has flown away.  I am playing the humble Servant but I know my Number is up & tonight I fly as well!"
> read crumpled page

> read crumpled page
"August 11, 1710

I fear the Captain has been foully Murdered, for he went fishing as usual (the way in watch he can catch a Fish now is a sight) but he has not let returned; however Skinny John who went sent to pick Fruit returned with far different demeanor & most damning he carried the same Witchery as was previously housed only in the Captain's person.  It is obvious to all what has befallen our beloved Captain & Cookie said as much.  Skinny John denies it but all but named himself Captain at once & the Captain's body not yet cold!   He says it was a Gift of the jungle which told him that he could find more such statues and become King of this place but I think he is Mad.  Cookie found drowned this evening & it looked like he had fallen in but of course that is more Tricks.   I am keeping one Eye on Rosie & one eye on my own Life."
> read yellowed page

> read yellowed page
"July 15th, 1710.

Those who survived the terrible storm were Myself and Rosie, Old Mad Jane, Skinny John, and Cookie.   Mister Edmund, Doxy Lu, and the new man (who I did not know well) are Drowned.  We feared the Captain lost overboard but found him clinging to the Hull and he laughed and said he that Captain Pisces would not die so Easily at such a little Drizzle.   However we are well and truly run aground and a good deal inland too.   We have fresh Water at least but not much Food left, must go hunting soon but such a place as this must be full of Beasts."
> x Guff

> x Guff
It's a sealed tin of Guff brand bubblegum snuff, the addictive rubber-tobacco hybrid that lets you blow bubbles from your nose.   It was very popular during the golden age of piracy, but interest waned when everyone realized what a bad idea it was.
> take Guff

> take Guff
You've never been one to take any Guff.
> x portrait

> x portrait
This large, elegantly painted portrait depicts a portly pirate captain -- Captain Horatio Harold Pritchard Pratchett Pisces, according to the plaque on the frame -- dressed in a mockery of admiral's finery.  His weathered face is split by a cheerful grin, but there's steel in his gaze and his arms are folded, as if he's guarding the enormous treasure behind him.   The artist went a little overboard depicting it, filling the space with a mountainous hoard of gold and gems that would turn ten dragons green with envy, and you get the sense that if anyone laid a finger on any of it Captain Pisces would gladly lop off the whole hand.    A baby parrot, little more than a tiny gray puffball, is perched on one of the Captain's shoulders.

The frame is pig iron and much heavier than you would figure a portait needed, and continues the 'security' theme -- it seems to have been made by halfway melting down a bunch of manacles and old locks and fusing them together.  Most of them have been warped and ruined by the process, but you spy a functional looking keyhole on the right side of the portrait.
